The vote on the Townsend plan amendment was not taken by roll call, but division.
Note: A division vote, also called a standing vote, is taken as follows: Members in favor of a proposal stand and are counted by a presiding officer; then Members opposed stand and are counted.
There is no record of how individual Members voted.
The members voting for the Townsend plan amendment, however, were listed in newspapers.
The majority of Members who voted for the Townsend plan were conservative Republicans who opposed the entire social security bill.
