c.
Payroll Tax Freeze.
1942-1947 Between 1942 and 1947, the social security payroll tax rate increase was
postponed seven times.
It was not until 1950 that the
percent social
tax rate was finally allowed to rise to 1.5 percent.
1.
The Revenue Act of 1942, P.L. 753 (H.R. 7378, 77th Congress) was signed into law by President Roosevelt on October 21, 1942.
It provided that for one year, from January 1, 1943, to January 1, 1944, the payroll tax rate for old-age and survivors benefits would be frozen at the existing rate of one percent for employees and employers each, instead of being increased to two percent on each as otherwise would have been required.
