Senate Action
a.
On December 5, 1969, Mr. Long (D-La.) offered an amendment to raise basic social security benefits by 15 percent beginning in January 1970.
Mr. Long's amendment was by a vote of 73 (23-R, 50-D) to 14 (14-R).
/ b.
A Byrd (D-W. Va.)-Mansfield (D-Mont.) amendment to increase the minimum benefit to $100 for single persons and to $150 for mar ried couples and to increase the taxable wage base from $7,800 to $12,000 beginning in 1973 was passed December 5, 1969, by a vote of 48 (8-R, 40-D) to 41 (28-R, 13-D).
1 c.
On December 5, 1969, Mr. Williams (R-Del.) offered a substitute for the Long amendment to provide a 10 percent benefit increase (instead of 15 percent).
The substitute amendment was rejected by a vote of 34 (33-R, 1-D) to 56 (S-R, 51-D).
