in the Senate to a House-passed bill that raised the debt limit (H.R. 15390).
The bill also provided for future automatic-increases in social security bene fits when the consumer price index (CPI) rose by three percent or more.
To finance the increase, the taxable wage base was raised from $9,000 to $10,800 in 1973 and to $12,000 in 1974, with automatic adjustment thereafter.
The Congressional Quarterly Almanac reported that: Backers of the social security benefits package decided to attach it to the debt increase bill for two reasons: President Nixon, who op posed a increase as inflationary, would be unlikely to veto a bill that contained a debt limit increase.
